[2] USA - Connecticut
Date: 17 Oct 2018
Source: Patch.com [edited]
https://patch.com/connecticut/naugatuck/increase-coxsackie-virus-naugatuck-public-schools


An increase in Coxsackie virus has been reported in Naugatuck [Connecticut] Public Schools. Naugatuck school nurses sent a letter to parents informing them of the virus, the text of which follows.

"There has been an increased occurrence of the Coxsackie virus, also known as hand-foot-mouth disease, in our student population.

"The Coxsackie virus is a viral illness that usually affects children younger than 5 [years]. However, some older children and even adults may get it. It typically starts with a fever, sore throat and a rash that may develop inside the mouth, on the hands, on the feet, and on the diaper area.

"It is spread through close personal contact, through the air (through coughing or sneezing), contact with feces, or through contact with contaminated objects. People are most contagious during the 1st week of the virus.

"If your child has any of these signs or symptoms, please keep them home from school. In order for a student to return to school, they must be fever free for 24 hours without the use of medication and have no open sores. If you are unsure as to whether your child should be in school, please contact their pediatrician or your school nurse.

"If your child was dismissed from school with an undiagnosed rash, a note from their medical provider must be submitted to the school nurse confirming the rash is non-contagious."

[Byline: Brian McCready]

