[Borrowed from Mod.LK: "Enteroviruses are the causative agents of hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD); included in the enteroviruses are polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, and enteroviruses. Enterovirus 71, a non-polio enterovirus, has been implicated in HFMD outbreaks in southeast Asia over the past several years. Complications associated with HFMD caused by the more pathogenic EV-71 strain include encephalitis, aseptic meningitis, acute flaccid paralysis, pulmonary edema or hemorrhage, and myocarditis. Most deaths from HFMD occur as a result of pulmonary edema or hemorrhage."

HFMD most often occurs in the spring and fall and is most frequently seen in young children, infants, and toddlers. It is characterized by fever and a blister-like rash affecting the palms of the hands and soles of the feet, along with blisters inside the mouth. (It is unrelated to foot and mouth disease, which affects livestock.)

There are no tests indicated in obvious cases of HFMD. The diagnosis is made based on the typical symptoms and signs found on examination. This is because the diagnostic laboratory tests that are available generally take 2 to 3 weeks to get results, and generally the symptoms of the illness will have resolved already by this time. - Mod.UBA

